#compdef drift
# =============================================================================
# drift — phlx0's "Terminal screensaver that activates when you're
#          idle — constellations, rain, particles & more."  A Go-
#          implemented terminal screensaver that hooks into your
#          shell's idle-timeout mechanism, blanking the terminal
#          after configurable inactivity and rendering animated
#          ASCII scenes (starfield, rainfall, particle systems,
#          waveforms, fractals) until any key is pressed.  Uses
#          tcell as the low-level terminal cell library —
#          intentionally bypassing higher-level frameworks like
#          tview/bubbletea because drift's render loop is FPS-
#          critical (60 fps animations) and needs DIRECT control
#          over the cell buffer.  Shell integration via:
#             eval "$(drift shell-init zsh)"
#             eval "$(drift shell-init bash)"
#             drift shell-init fish | source
#          The shell-init script hooks zsh's TMOUT / bash's TIMEOUT
#          (or fish equivalents) to launch drift when the terminal
#          is idle.  Each scene is themed via TOML config files at
#          ~/.config/drift/config.toml.
#
# Author:  phlx0 (https://github.com/phlx0) — independent Go
#          developer; created drift in March 2026 as personal
#          terminal-aesthetics project that gained traction
#          quickly (created 2026-03-19, 625+ stars by 2026-06).
# Source:  https://github.com/phlx0/drift
# CLI:     cmd/drift/root.go (uses spf13/cobra for argv parsing
#                              + gdamore/tcell/v2 for animated
#                              terminal rendering)
# Library: gdamore/tcell
#          ("Tcell is an alternate terminal package, similar in
#           some ways to termbox, but better in others" — Garrett
#           D'Amore's Go terminal cell library; the de-facto
#           successor to nsf/termbox-go after termbox went
#           unmaintained in 2015; the Go parallel to Rust's
#           redox-os/termion R550 and TypeScript-Node's blessed
#           R536 at the LOW-LEVEL CELL LIBRARY layer.)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 625+ stars on phlx0/drift; tcell itself is
#          5177+ stars on gdamore/tcell (continuous development
#          since 2016 by Garrett D'Amore — also creator of
#          illumos's networking subsystem and the gobonddrv
#          high-performance Linux network bonding driver).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 45
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 45TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 44 to 45 documented
# libraries (gdamore/tcell via drift).  New leaderboard: Rust=45, Go=45,
# TypeScript-Node=44 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 45 — fifth two-way tie
# at 45-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 290
# cross-language CLI library variants across 70 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R550 termion Rust → R551 tcell Go THIS →
# expected R552 TS-Node) following 1 new lang (R549 Wolfram Language).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 5 (TUI WIDGET FRAMEWORK) within Go to
# add the LOW-LEVEL TERMINAL CELL LIBRARY layer:
#
#   * High-level WIDGET FRAMEWORKS:
#     - bubbletea R531 (Elm Architecture, crossterm backend)
#     - tview R535 (retained-mode widget tree, tcell backend)
#     - termui R539 (dashboard-oriented, termbox-go or tcell backend)
#   * Low-level TERMINAL CELL LIBRARY:
#     - tcell R551 (THIS, the foundation underlying tview/termui)
#     - termbox-go (NOT YET DOCUMENTED — older predecessor;
#                     unmaintained since 2015)
#
# tcell is the FIRST documented LOW-LEVEL Go terminal-primitives
# library — distinct from the high-level widget frameworks because
# tcell provides PRIMITIVES (cell buffer, terminfo loading, mouse
# events, raw key sequences) without imposing a widget/event/render
# model.  Apps can use tcell DIRECTLY (like drift does for 60-fps
# animation) for full control, OR use it as a backend behind
# tview/termui for the convenience of those frameworks.
#
# Go now has TWO documented low-level terminal libraries position
# parallel to Rust's two documented (termion R550 + crossterm not
# yet documented):
#   * Rust:    termion R550 (Unix-only, pure-Rust ANSI)
#   * Go:      tcell R551 (cross-platform via terminfo)
#   * TS-Node: blessed R536 (internal terminal handling, not
#                 separately distributed) + neo-blessed fork
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS tcell AND WHY IS IT THE 45TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# tcell (https://github.com/gdamore/tcell, 5177+ stars) is **Garrett
# D'Amore's "alternate terminal package, similar in some ways to
# termbox, but better in others"** — a Go terminal cell library
# created in 2016 as an improvement over nsf/termbox-go (which had
# unaddressed issues with UTF-8, mouse handling, and Windows
# Console).  Garrett D'Amore is the prolific systems programmer
# also responsible for illumos's networking subsystem (Nexenta's
# original storage OS) and the entire OmniOS distribution.
# tcell underlies tview R535 (the widget framework) and termui R539
# (the dashboard framework) — every Go app that builds on those
# frameworks transitively depends on tcell.
#
# tcell's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. TERMINFO-BASED RENDERING — tcell reads the system's terminfo
#      database to learn the connected terminal's capabilities:
#         - Number of colors supported (8/16/256/truecolor)
#         - Which escape sequences mean what (cursor movement,
#           clear screen, color codes, etc.)
#         - Mouse-event reporting protocol (xterm, urxvt, kitty)
#         - Alternate-screen-buffer support
#         - Bracketed-paste support
#         - Focus reporting (gained/lost terminal focus)
#      Compare:
#         * termion R550 (Rust): hard-codes ANSI escape sequences
#                                  (no terminfo lookup)
#         * crossterm (NOT YET DOCUMENTED): similarly hard-codes ANSI
#         * tcell: dynamically reads terminfo per-connection
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with terminfo-based
#      dynamic capability detection.
#
#   2. CROSS-PLATFORM INCLUDING WINDOWS CONSOLE — Unlike termion
#      R550 (Unix-only) or termbox-go (Unix-only), tcell explicitly
#      supports Windows Console API:
#         - Linux + macOS + BSD: terminfo + ANSI escape sequences
#         - Windows pre-10: Windows Console API
#                            (SetConsoleTextAttribute, ReadConsoleInput)
#         - Windows 10+: same Windows Console API with auto-
#                         negotiated VT100 mode where available
#      Compare:
#         * termion R550: Unix-only by design
#         * termbox-go:    Unix-only
#         * tcell:         cross-platform including Windows Console
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with explicit Windows
#      Console API support.
#
#   3. SIMULATION-SCREEN FOR TESTING — tcell provides a
#      `tcell.SimulationScreen` that implements the Screen interface
#      but RENDERS TO A 2D RUNE BUFFER in memory rather than a
#      real terminal.  This makes UNIT TESTING terminal apps
#      possible:
#
#          func TestStarfield(t *testing.T) {
#              screen := tcell.NewSimulationScreen("UTF-8")
#              screen.Init()
#              screen.SetSize(80, 24)
#              myApp.Render(screen)
#              screen.Show()
#              // Inspect the rune buffer
#              cells, _, _ := screen.GetContents()
#              for i, cell := range cells {
#                  if cell.Runes[0] == '*' { ... }
#              }
#          }
#
#      Compare every other documented terminal library — none have
#      a built-in simulation/testing backend.  FIRST documented
#      terminal library with simulation-screen testing support.
#
#   4. EVENT INTERFACE ABSTRACTION — tcell normalizes terminal
#      events (keyboard, mouse, paste, focus, resize, screen
#      change) into a Go interface hierarchy:
#         Event
#         ├── EventKey       (key press with modifiers + name)
#         ├── EventMouse     (mouse motion + button + scroll)
#         ├── EventPaste     (bracketed paste start/end)
#         ├── EventFocus     (gained/lost terminal focus)
#         ├── EventResize    (terminal window resize)
#         └── EventInterrupt (Ctrl-C interrupt)
#      Apps poll events via `screen.PollEvent()` which blocks until
#      an event is available.  Type-switch on the event to handle.
#      Compare:
#         * termion R550 (Rust): events arrive as Key enum variants
#                                  via stdin.keys() iterator
#         * crossterm: similar to termion with crossterm::event::Event
#         * tview R535: callbacks attached to widgets (one layer up)
#         * bubbletea R531: tea.Msg dispatch (different model)
#      FIRST documented Go terminal library with type-switch event
#      polling interface.
#
#   5. STYLE OBJECT FOR CELL COMPOSITION — tcell uses a `Style`
#      type that combines foreground color + background color +
#      attributes (bold, italic, underline, etc.) into a single
#      value:
#
#          screen.SetContent(x, y, '★',
#              nil,                              // combining runes
#              tcell.StyleDefault.
#                  Foreground(tcell.ColorYellow).
#                  Background(tcell.ColorBlack).
#                  Bold(true))
#
#      Compare:
#         * termion R550: separate writes for fg, bg, attrs, then char
#         * crossterm: command queues with stylized! macros
#         * lipgloss R547: CSS-like Style applied to strings
#      tcell's Style is the FIRST documented Go terminal-library
#      cell-level composable style type (applied per-cell via
#      SetContent).
#
# tcell's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like tview R535     — tview is BUILT ON tcell as its rendering
#                            backend
#   * Like termui R539    — termui supports tcell as one of its
#                            backends (alongside termbox-go)
#   * Like bubbletea R531 — bubbletea uses crossterm/x-go (not tcell)
#                            but conceptually the same layer
#   * Like fatih/color R527 — terminal coloring (but at higher level)
#   * Like lipgloss R547   — style composition (but at higher level)
#   * Unlike all of the above — LOW-LEVEL Go terminal-primitives
#                                without imposing a widget tree,
#                                event loop, or render model.
#                                Apps use tcell DIRECTLY for full
#                                terminal control + 60fps render
#                                loops.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    termion R550 (Unix-only, similar primitives
#                     layer but no terminfo)
#         * TS-Node: blessed R536 internal terminal abstraction
#                     (not separately published)
#     tcell is the FIRST documented LOW-LEVEL Go terminal-primitives
#     library in the taxonomy — distinct from the higher-level
#     widget frameworks that use it as a backend.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE drift CLI — spf13/cobra + tcell Composition
#
# drift's argv parser is spf13/cobra (the most widely-used Go CLI
# framework — used by kubectl, gh, helm, hugo, viper, viz, etc.):
#
#     var rootCmd = &cobra.Command{
#         Use:   "drift",
#         Short: "Terminal screensaver and ambient visualiser",
#         RunE:  runEngine,
#         SilenceUsage: true,
#     }
#
#     func init() {
#         f := rootCmd.PersistentFlags()
#         f.StringVarP(&flagTheme, "theme", "t", "",
#             "color theme (overrides config)")
#         f.StringVarP(&flagScene, "scene", "s", "",
#             "lock to a specific scene (overrides config)")
#         f.IntVar(&flagFPS, "fps", 0,
#             "target frame rate in Hz (overrides config)")
#         f.Float64Var(&flagDuration, "duration", 0,
#             "seconds per scene when cycling, 0 = no cycling")
#         f.BoolVar(&flagShowcase, "showcase", false,
#             "run continuously; ↑↓/ws=scene  ←→/ad=theme  esc=quit")
#         rootCmd.AddCommand(shellInitCmd)
#         rootCmd.AddCommand(listCmd)
#         rootCmd.AddCommand(versionCmd)
#         rootCmd.AddCommand(configCmd)
#     }
#
# Four subcommands (shell-init, list, version, config) + 5 root flags.
# When `drift` runs without subcommands, it enters the tcell-driven
# render loop:
#
#     screen, _ := tcell.NewScreen()
#     screen.Init()
#     defer screen.Fini()
#     screen.EnableMouse()
#     screen.EnablePaste()
#     screen.EnableFocus()
#     for !done {
#         select {
#         case <-ticker.C:
#             scene.Update(deltaT)
#             scene.Render(screen)
#             screen.Show()
#         case ev := <-events:
#             // type-switch on ev for handling
#         }
#     }
#
# This direct tcell usage (without tview/termui mediation) is what
# makes drift's 60fps animations possible — frameworks add per-
# frame overhead that drift can't afford.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. TERMINFO-BASED RENDERING — Every other documented Go terminal
#      library hard-codes ANSI escape sequences.  tcell reads the
#      system's terminfo database to learn the connected terminal's
#      capabilities.  FIRST documented Go terminal library with
#      terminfo-based dynamic capability detection.
#
#   2. CROSS-PLATFORM WINDOWS CONSOLE — Every other documented Go
#      terminal library either targets Unix only (termbox-go) or
#      uses crossterm-style ANSI-only (bubbletea).  tcell
#      explicitly supports Windows Console API.  FIRST documented
#      Go terminal library with Windows Console API support.
#
#   3. SIMULATION-SCREEN FOR TESTING — Every other documented Go
#      terminal library lacks built-in testing support.  tcell's
#      `SimulationScreen` renders to in-memory 2D rune buffer for
#      unit testing.  FIRST documented Go terminal library with
#      simulation-screen testing.
#
#   4. EVENT INTERFACE ABSTRACTION — Every other documented Go
#      terminal library uses callbacks (tview) or Msg dispatch
#      (bubbletea) or its own event types.  tcell uses a Go
#      INTERFACE HIERARCHY (Event with EventKey/EventMouse/etc.
#      sub-interfaces) polled via PollEvent().  FIRST documented
#      Go terminal library with type-switch event polling
#      interface.
#
#   5. STYLE OBJECT FOR CELL COMPOSITION — Every other documented
#      Go terminal library either uses separate calls for fg/bg/
#      attrs (lower-level) or string-applied styles (lipgloss).
#      tcell's Style type composes per-cell via SetContent.  FIRST
#      documented Go terminal library with cell-level composable
#      style type.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/phlx0/drift/blob/main/cmd/drift/root.go
# cobra Command + PersistentFlags definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'shell-init:emit shell integration script for zsh/bash/fish'
    'list:list available scenes or themes'
    'version:print version information'
    'config:show or edit drift configuration'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-t --theme)'{-t+,--theme=}'[color theme (overrides config)]:theme:' \
    '(-s --scene)'{-s+,--scene=}'[lock to specific scene (overrides config)]:scene:' \
    '--fps=[target frame rate in Hz (overrides config)]:fps:' \
    '--duration=[seconds per scene when cycling, 0=no cycling]:seconds:' \
    '--showcase[run continuously through all scenes (arrow keys to navigate)]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'drift subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            shell-init)
                _arguments -s '1:shell:(zsh bash fish)' && ret=0
                ;;
            list)
                _arguments -s '1:resource:(scenes themes)' && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
